ality, LGBTQ rights, environmental conservation, ethnic relations, and candidate evaluations.Voicing Politics traces how these patterns emerge in polities spanning the globe, shedding essential light on how simple linguistic quirks can affect our political views. This incisive book calls on scholars of political behavior to take linguistic nuances more seriously and charts new directions for researchers across diverse fields. It explains how a stronger grasp of linguistic effects on political cognition can help us better understand how people form political attitudes and why political outcomes vary across nations and regions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLanguage and languages-Political aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / General.2bisacsh  aAdult.  aAffair.  aAll things.  aAutomaticity.  aBehavior.  aBibliography.  aCitizenship.  aClimate Action.  aCognition.  aConfidence interval.  aConsideration.  aConvenience.  aDemocratization.  aDichotomy.  aEconomic growth.  aEnvironmental protection.  aEthnic group.  aEurobarometer.  aEurostat.  aExperimental political science.  aExternal validity.  aFinding.  aFinnish language.  aFirst language.  aFluency.  aForay.  aFreedom of speech.  aFuel tax.  aFuture tense.  aGender equality.  aGender neutrality.  aGender role.  aGender-specific and gender-neutral pronouns.  aGenderless language.  aGeneral Social Survey.  aGeorge Lakoff.  aGrammar.  aHeuristic.  aIdentity politics.  aIdeology.  aImmigration.  aInference.  aInterview.  aInterviewer effect.  aLGBT.  aLanguage.  aLatent variable.  aLatino (demonym).  aLinguistic relativity.  aMetaphor.  aMilitary occupation.  aMinority group.  aMinority language.  aMoral reasoning.  aMr.  aMulticulturalism. 